43,Dishonesty-and-justifications--Evidence-fro_2026_Journal-of-Behavioral-and-E.pdf,"Both coauthors appear to have 
published using altered or falsified data, with the responsibility for this 
contested. We are not aware of any specific allegations with regard to 
this publication, though the data have some odd features which are 
discussed in the Online Appendix, Section 1. These general and specific 
concerns lead us to re-examine the theory of Justified Dishonesty. The current evidence base for Justified Dishonesty comprises three 
elements. First, Justified Dishonesty’s predictions of the mean and 
distribution of reports have been shown to be remarkably accurate. The 
most comprehensive evidence failed to reject Justified Dishonesty in 
13 of 23 countries (Gächter & Schulz, 2016; Shalvi, 2016), showing 
wide applicability. Second, multiple rolls increase mean claims (Gino 
& Ariely, 2012; Shalvi et al., 2011, 2012), with Abeler et al.’s (2019) 
meta analysis finding an effect size of between one fifth and one 
twentieth of a standard deviation. Third, there is suggestive evidence 
on mechanisms, with the switching of rolls being rated less negatively 
than outright lying (Shalvi et al., 2011). On closer inspection, the evidence base is inconclusive. First, we 
show that a good fit to data does not distinguish Justified Dishonesty 
from other models (Dufwenberg & Dufwenberg, 2018; Khalmetski & 
Sliwka, 2019), as its predictions are not unique. This means a good 
fit to data is not sufficient evidence that Justified Dishonesty explains 
behaviour. Second, the evidence that control rolls increase mean claims 
does not unambiguously support the theory, as its specific prediction 
about the level of lying is not met. Third, there is currently no evidence 
on the specific mechanism of Justified Dishonesty, i.e. that subjects 
‘‘shuffle’’ rolls when it pays to do so (Shalvi et al. (2012, p.1267), Shalvi 
et al. (2015, p.127), Shalvi (2016, p.457)). Fourth, Baro et al. (2024) 
use an online observed design, and find cheating is influenced by 
control rolls. However, a self-reported scale of moral self image is not, 
questioning the mechanism. We conduct two experiments in order to separate between compet-
ing explanations of lying behaviour. Other studies show that the mean 
and spread of reports closely match Justified Dishonesty’s predictions 
when subjects are encouraged to roll twice. In experiment 1, we ask 
whether this also occurs when subjects are asked to report their first 
