We designed our experiments in order to test Justified Dishonesty’s 
specific mechanism, but our data are informative to consider other 
possibilities. This section is exploratory, using methods that were not 
preregistered. We first use data from both rolls to assess model fit, 
rather than examining each rolls separately. Next, we relax the idea 
that Justified Dishonesty must be implemented by all subjects using 
mixture models to capture if it captures an element of behaviour that 
other models do not. We then turn our attention to two open questions 
— whether our design leads to people altering their first report, and 
how to think about the second report. 6.1. Using data from both rolls to assess model fit
We have looked so far at the two reports in isolation — testing the 
predictions of models on the two rolls independently. We can further 
exploit the data by using the combination of both rolls, i.e. by using 
all 36 cells. Fig. 5 presents the data from experiment 1 (bottom row) 
and experiment 2 (right hand side of the top row). For context, it also 
shows predictions from luck (i.e. an honest reporting of chance rolls) 
and Justified Dishonesty (and its corollary). Experiment 1 data is shown for completeness — Justified Dishon-
esty should not be relevant. Using experiment 2, we can calculate 
statistics for model fit. We use the 36 cells shown in Fig. 5 as the 
dependent variable, calibrating relevant models. For the second roll 
we either use the corollary (Justified Dishonesty) or assume honest 
reporting of the second roll (all other cases). Table  4 presents statistics for model fit, showing a clear order 
of model performance. Dufwenberg and Dufwenberg’s (2018) model 
fits the data best, fairly closely followed by Khalmetski and Sliwka’s 
(2019) model. Assuming people report honestly is the third best model, 
with Justified Dishonesty and its corollary producing the least accurate 
predictions. In all but one case all statistics in both treatments have 
