that no exceptions to the age-of-marriage tend to be associated with an 
increase in child marriage. These results suggest that the gap between 
legal reforms and local perceptions may have been too wide to serve as a 
magnet to reform customs. This is particularly the case if there is no 
credible risk of monitoring and enforcement. The latter seems to play an 
important role, as the regression analyses show that mandatory regis -
tration is associated with a consistent and significant reduction in child 
marriage rates. Other important aspects are possible ways to circumvent the law and 
the political willingness to enforce it. Court rulings that got much media 
attention and enforced laws tend to be more effective; however, there is 
an important tradeoff between formal and informal marriages that in -
dividuals seem to largely exploit in response to legal changes. Thus, one 
should be careful about the unintended consequences of legal changes in 
places where strong social norms persist. Taken together, the detailed analysis of the legal texts shows that 
child marriage laws cannot be treated as uniform and are far from being 
readily comparable. This is shown equally in the respective country- 
level marriage trends and regression analyses, which cannot be consis -
tently reconciled with legal actions. Yet, once we dissect the local 
context, we find evidence that the observed macro-level trends are an 
aggregate reflection of behavioral responses to the nationally imple -
mented age-of-marriage laws. While our research is descriptive and cannot establish causal re -
lationships, since formal and informal institutions may co-produce each 
other, it represents a first attempt to identify behavioral responses on a 
large scale and in a cross-country context to a seemingly straightforward 
minimum age-of-marriage law. We highlight national loopholes, delays 
in timing, legal pluralism, the relation between informal and formal 
institutions, the civil registration and vital statistics system, and other 
contextual factors to explain why existing research into the de -
terminants of child marriage has not managed to provide a coherent 
picture of the observed lived practices across contexts. Put differently, 
our document analysis and exploratory regression models disentangle 
the nuances of formal and informal marriage institutions. While not 
offering causal insights, our study complements impact evaluation 
