 A B S T R A C T
Lobbying is commonly expected to reduce climate protection. Does such a belief affect individuals’ own 
climate protection efforts? According to conditional cooperation, for example, it should discourage individuals 
from contributing. I investigate this issue of high policy relevance using an online experiment with a large 
heterogeneous sample from the German population. To identify the causal effect of citizens’ beliefs about the 
impact of lobbying on climate protection, I induce exogenous variation in these beliefs and measure subsequent 
individual behavior. I find some evidence for a discouragement effect: Expecting a more negative impact of 
lobbying reduces individual contributions to climate protection. While not all considered behaviors show a 
significant effect, treatment differences consistently point in the same direction. These results emphasize the 
risk of spillover effects through citizens’ beliefs and lend support to a more holistic approach when evaluating 
the consequences of lobbying or climate policies. 1. Introduction
Lobbying is a billion-dollar industry (OECD, 2012) that relies on 
different strategies to influence political decision-making. Previous re-
search shows that lobbying can be effective in exerting influence (e.g., 
Gawande et al., 2006; Giger & Klüver, 2016; Igan & Mishra, 2014; 
Markussen & Svendsen, 2005) and in securing substantial returns for 
the lobbying party (de Figueiredo & Silverman, 2006; Kang, 2016). For example, Kang (2016) estimates that lobbying by the energy 
sector during the 110th U.S. Congress had a significant impact on the 
enactment of policies, with the returns from lobbying expenditures 
exceeding 130 percent. In light of this evidence, it is not surprising that 
people’s perception of lobbying is rather negative. An often held belief 
is that lobbying negatively affects policy-making and primarily benefits 
businesses and politicians instead of citi…",
245,Does-lobbying-discourage-individuals-from_2025_Journal-of-Behavioral-and-Exp.pdf,"For example, participants in Group Negative are 32 percent 
more likely to expect a negative impact of lobbying on climate pro-
tection than participants in Group Positive. Exploiting this variation 
to identify the causal effect of beliefs, I find that participants who 
have been induced to hold more negative beliefs report significantly 
less contributions to climate and environmental protection for the 
post-experimental period (average treatment effect of −0.13 standard 
deviations, 95% CI: [−0.22, −0.04]). The most substantial effect comes 
from the likelihood of (not) taking a plane. However, all self-reported 
behaviors point in the same direction – i.e., more negative beliefs lead 
to less pro-climate behavior – and the effects on the joint measure 
as well as the single behavior of (not) taking a plane are robust to 
multiple hypothesis correction. While the estimated treatment effect on 
the observed contribution to carbon emission reductions also suggests 
a slightly negative impact of holding more negative beliefs, it is not 
significant at any conventional level (average treatment effect of −0.06
standard deviations, 95% CI: [−0.14, 0.03]). Hence, the results offer 
some evidence that beliefs about lobbying affect pro-climate behavior 
on the individual level, but they also suggest that the causal link might 
not be equally pronounced across the range of relevant behaviors. The paper contributes to three strands of the literature. First, it 
complements previous research on the consequences of lobbying by 
investigating a potential spillover effect that has received little at-
tention so far. Several studies investigate whether and how lobbying 
influences political decision-making (e.g., Bertrand et al., 2020; Giger 
& Klüver, 2016; Igan & Mishra, 2014; for a review, see de Figueiredo 
& Richter, 2014), including the context of environmental and climate 
policy (Gullberg, 2008; Kang, 2016; Markussen & Svendsen, 2005; 
Meng & Rode, 2019). However, little is known about whether – in 
addition to a direct impact of lobbying – the public perception of 
lobbying might cause behavioral adjustments on the individual level. This spillover can be a relevant factor in assessing the welfare effects 
of lobbying, particularly in the context of climate protection, where 
massive action of all actors is needed to mitigate the risk of severe 
consequences. Second and more generally, this paper contributes to a large litera-
ture on the determinants of pro-e…",
