361,Avoiding-cognitive-inconsistency--Experimenta_2025_Journal-of-Behavioral-and.pdf,"Not least, this is the first study to examine the effects of increased 
salience of cognitive inconsistency in the context of sustainable online 
shopping — a topic of growing importance. In 2024, the global share of 
online shopping over total sales amounted to 20%, generating revenues 
of more than 4.1 trillion US$, and this share is expected to continue 
rising (van Gelder, 2024). In Germany, where this study was conducted, 
60% of the population made online purchases in 2023 (Koptyug, 2025). At the same time, online shopping has a significant environmental 
impact due to high carbon emissions, excessive packaging, resource 
consumption, and waste (Forbes, 2020; Irgini, 2024; Oceana, 2020). Addressing these challenges requires the adoption of eco-friendly 
practices in logistics, packaging, and production, as well as fair labor 
and responsible sourcing policies, all while fostering greater demand 
for sustainably produced products. However, evidence regarding the 
role of sustainability in online shopping is scarce and inconclusive: 
While some studies suggest that sustainability aspects play only a minor 
role for online shopping (Rausch et al., 2021) — possibly even less than 
for offline shopping (Ermecke et al., 2023) — others point toward an 
increased importance of sustainability (Jacobs et al., 2018). The subsequent Sections 2 and 3 explain the underlying theoretical 
model and the experimental design and hypotheses, respectively. Sec-
tion 4 describes the data employed for our empirical analysis. Section 5 
presents the results, while the last section summarizes and concludes. 2. Theoretical underpinnings
Our theoretical analysis builds upon Konow (2000) and Rabin 
(1994), who developed rational choice models in which cognitive disso-
nance negatively affects utility ‘‘because it is unpleasant’’ (Rabin, 1994, 
p. 178). Accordingly, individuals try to avoid cognitive inconsistency 
and the potentially resulting cognitive dissonance, either by adjusting 
their behavior to fit their beliefs about what is moral, or by modifying 
these beliefs to fit their behavior, that is, by deceiving themselves. Both options come at a cost: Adapting behavior may reduce utility, 
whereas changing beliefs causes cognitive unease because ‘‘there is 
likely to be a natural [...] set of beliefs about the morality of an 
activity’’ (Rabin, 1994, p. 180) and an ‘‘intellectually honest view of 
what is fair’’ (Konow, 2000, p. 1077). Individuals therefore balance the 
ma…",
