ABSTRACT
In a laboratory experiment, this study investigates the effectiveness of different behavioural interventions 
designed to promote climate-friendly behaviours within the framework of a public good game. The results show 
that educative nudging, which involves providing information-based cues to encourage contribution levels, 
significantly increased participant cooperation levels. In contrast, non-educative nudges, a classical default op -
tion, and boosting techniques proved less effective in fostering collaborative behaviour. While participants 
generally perceived educational interventions favourably, their acceptability declined when considering real-life 
applications, and the acceptability of nudging/boosting instruments in experimental and real-life contexts was 
not significant in terms of contributions to the game. The study also finds that individuals with stronger envi -
ronmental values were more inclined to contribute to the public good. These results underscore the importance 
of effectiveness and ethical concerns regarding the acceptability of behavioural interventions in decision-making, 
suggesting the need for further research to refine these approaches and enhance their long-term impact in real- 
world settings. 1. Introduction
The pressing challenge of climate change and the urgent need to 
reduce CO2 emissions call for a multidimensional approach that en -
compasses not only policies and technologies but also behavioural 
changes at both individual and collective levels. In this context, 
behavioural intervention techniques have taken on an increasingly 
prominent role, providing strategies to influence individuals ’ choices 
toward more sustainable behaviours. This study aims to explore the 
effectiveness of various behavioural strategies, including educative 
nudges, non-educative nudges, and boosting, in promoting pro-social 
behaviours within the context of a public goods game designed to 
reduce CO2 emissions. Through empiri…",
473,Evaluating-behavioural-strategies-for-environme_2025_Journal-of-Behavioral-a.pdf,"These nudges 
may include informational campaigns, feedback mechanisms, educa -
tional workshops, and other interventions that increase awareness and 
promote understanding of the reasoning process, thereby empowering 
individuals to make more thoughtful decisions. Educative nudges in the 
form of informational content may also encourage behaviour that ben -
efits others or the community. For example, Schultz et al. (2007) found 
that high-energy-consuming households tend to decrease their con -
sumption when informed about the average usage in their neighbour -
hood. More recently, Bhanot (2021) found that norm messaging (e.g., a 
smiley, neutral, or frowny face depending on water consumption) can 
encourage water conservation by reducing water use by 1–5 %. Simi -
larly, Huitink et al. (2020) found that supermarket customers increased 
their vegetable purchases after receiving messages about other cus -
tomers’ vegetable-buying habits. Khanal et al. (2025) used information-based nudges to influence 
consumer meat choices. They found that comparative, goat-focused 
information—emphasising how goat meat’s attributes compare with 
those of other meats—was significantly more effective than providing 
generic information. Their results suggest that, when supported by 
appropriate information, goat meat could represent a viable alternative 
to conventional meats, particularly for consumers seeking healthier and 
more environmentally sustainable options. These findings underscore 
the potential of informational content as a behavioural change tool 
( Barron & Nurminen, 2020 ). Nevertheless, the broader academic liter -
ature offers mixed evidence on the effectiveness of informational nudges 
across different contexts. For instance, Clark et al. (2014) found that a simple informational 
flyer about tax-advantaged retirement savings increased participation 
by 2.5 percentage points among younger workers, but demonstrated no 
