broa…",
517,Gender-of-the-opponent-and-reaction-to-_2025_Journal-of-Behavioral-and-Exper.pdf,"Empirical evidence indicates that women are 
more likely than men to drop out after setbacks, especially in male-
dominated fields (Buser & Yuan, 2019; Ellis, Fosdick, & Rasmussen, 
2016; Price, 2010). Therefore, understanding how men and women 
react to winning or losing, and whether these reactions depend on the 
opponent’s gender, provides valuable insights into labor market dynam-
ics. Additionally, our study explores how prior competitive outcomes, 
particularly unexpected losses, influence subsequent decisions to re-
enter competition. The controlled setting of a lab experiment allows 
us to isolate and examine these behavioral responses. The seminal experimental study on gender differences in willingness 
to compete is Niederle and Vesterlund (2007). It documents, in a 
lab experiment, a significant gender gap in tournament entry, driven 
by men being more overconfident and more willing to perform in 
a competition. Subsequent research has consistently confirmed that 
men tend to be more confident and competitive than women (Alan, 
Ertac, Kubilay, & Loranth, 2020; Dreber et al., 2014; Kamas & Preston, 
2012; Ludwig, Fellner-Röhling, & Thoma, 2017). This leads to an over-
representation of low-performing men and an under-representation of 
high-performing women in competitive settings. While in a lab envi-
ronment, these suboptimal choices directly affect individuals’ earnings, 
at a broader level, a loss of efficiency is incurred if qualified women 
are not assigned to high positions in favor of less competent men. The 
analysis of public interventions, aimed at reducing the gender gap in 
competitiveness and in the labor market, shows that these differences 
are not irreversible (Balafoutas & Sutter, 2012; Beaman et al., 2012). Moving from individual characteristics to competition features,
Buser, van den Assem, and van Dolder (2023) test and confirm the 
validity of gender differences in competitive preferences in a quasi-
experimental real-world setting with exceptionally high stakes.4 In 
this study, the authors also analyze how the gender of the opponent 
influences the decision to enter competition, finding that women tend 
to avoid competing against men. On the other hand, men seem to 
anticipate female behavior and show a greater willingness to compete 
against women. In contrast, when considering hormonal influences, 
women appear more responsive than men to the characteristics of their 
opponent. Brañas-Garza, Chowdhury, Espín, and Nieboer…",
