ABSTRACT
This paper examines the role of peers ’ performance feedback on individual productivity in competitive envi -
ronments. We specifically study the link between individual performance and the past performance of teammates 
and opposing teams. We use a dataset on all the penalty kicks in knockout stages of World Cup and European Cup 
competitions in male soccer from 1976 to 2024. We find that the probability of scoring a penalty kick is 17.9 
percentage points lower after the opponent team scored a kick but does not change with the outcome of a 
teammate ’ s penalty kick. Our evidence supports the notion that individuals ’ underperformance when feeling 
pressure ( “ choking under pressure ” ) is primarily driven by feedback on competitors ’ performance, rather than by 
teammates ’ performance. 1. Introduction
When performing in high-pressure competitions, individuals often 
perform in an unexpected way compared to their level of skills ( Genakos 
et al., 2015 ). Although greater incentives increase effort ( Lazear & 
Rosen, 1981 ), the psychological pressure arising from high payoffs and 
the fear of failure can lead to a deterioration in performance, a phe -
nomenon commonly known as “ choking under pressure ” . This anxiety 
and stress that competitors experience in highly contested environments 
vary depending on whether agents perform individually or as part of a 
team. In team settings, the social dimension also plays a role. In this 
context, there is an additional source of psychological pressure: The 
feeling of guilt associated with failing to meet others ’ expectations in 
case of subpar performance ( Charness & Dufwenberg, 2006 ). There are many competitive contexts where individuals perform 
sequential teamwork. Examples include corporate businesses that 
compete for sales targets, management consulting firms that work on 
client projects, hackathon contests for software programmers, and sport 
teams. In dynamic settings, individuals typically receive signals about 
their own and their opposing teams ’ productivity. From the point of 
view of a rational agent, any performance feedback should change the 
pri…",
549,Return-intentions-of-Ukrainian-refugees--The_2025_Journal-of-Behavioral-and-.pdf,"Although the general economic factors behind the pref-
erences to migrate and return and the implications of these decisions 
for the host and home countries have been discussed, little is known 
about non-economic motivations behind return intent of war refugees. 2.2. Return intent of refugees: security concerns and psychological factors
Economic models of migrations do not explicitly accommodate war 
refugees which might have other motivations for or against return than 
economic migrants. Research on war refugees from Syria identifies 
security situation and living conditions (e.g. electricity supply) as one 
of the most important factors behind decisions to return (Beaman, 
Onder, & Onder, 2022). Camarena and Hägerdal (2020) and Gosn et al. (2021) underline the role of psychological attachments to home and 
host country alongside security and economic concerns. By looking at 
World War II evacuees in Finland Lynch et al. (2019) find a strong 
link between ‘‘social bonding’’ (marriage and fertility choices) and 
likelihood to return. Meta-review of Hagen-Zanker, Hennessey, and 
Mazzilli (2023) reveals an increasing role of psychological factors, such 
as feeling of hope, personality traits, and mental representations of the 
host and the home countries. Müller (2019) suggests that imagining 
the future and (lack of) hope in the home country reduce the desire 
of Syrian refugees to return; Debray, Ruyssen, and Schewel (2025) 
mentions hope for improvements in the home country among the 
factors behind preferences to stay. 2.3. Social identity and return intentions
Social identity, broadly defined as the sense of belonging to a social 
category or group (Tajfel & Turner, 1979, Tajfel & Turner, 1986, Hogg 
& Williams, 2000) has long been known to affect people’s (economic) 
behavior (Akerlof & Kranton, 2000, Akerlof & Kranton, 2010, Davis, 
2010). The main premise of this approach is that group membership shapes 
individual behavior, i.e. individuals derive extra utility from aligning 
their behavior to the one prescribed by the group norms (Reynolds, 
2019, Muldoon, Lisciandra, Bicchieri, Hartmann, & Sprenger, 2014). Research has shown that (various types of) social identity affects peo-
ple’s social, risk, time preferences and cooperation (Benjamin, Choi, & 
Strickland, 2010, Benjamin, Choi, & Fisher, 2016, Chen, Li, Liu, & Shih, 
2014). We define national identity as ‘‘a subjective or internalized sense 
of belonging to the nation’’ (See, Huddy & Khatib…",
555,Return-intentions-of-Ukrainian-refugees--The_2025_Journal-of-Behavioral-and-.pdf,"For 
participants with above-the-mean values of dispositional national iden-
tity (to the right of the red vertical line indicating the mean identity 
score), our identity-salience manipulation generated higher return in-
tentions compared to a control condition. This supports our Hypothesis 
2a: salience increases the willingness to return for participants with a 
high level of national identity. Fig. 2 depicts an interesting different pattern: for the below-the-
mean values of pride (to the left of the red vertical line indicating 
the mean pride score in the sample), salience manipulation decreases 
the willingness to return. For the above-the-mean values of pride (to 
the right of the red vertical line indicating the mean pride score in 
the sample), the salience manipulation does not have any effect on 
intention return. This observation supports our Hypothesis 2b: salience of pride 
decreases the willingness to return for participants with low levels of 
pride. This finding of the negative effect of pride salience has very im-
portant policy implications. It suggests that for people who developed 
low pride levels (e.g. due to no major successes on the battlefield, 
or pre-war unhappiness with economic prospects or the development 
of civic institutions), the pride-salience interventions might backfire. National identity salience seems to matter more for people who score 
high on the identity values prior to an intervention. Therefore, for the 
salience manipulation to be effective, a long-term shift in dispositional 
national identity might be needed. This shift might require investment 
into maintaining the link with Ukraine, e.g. by supporting Ukrainian 
cultural and educational programs in the diaspora. 6. Discussion and conclusions
We have conducted a large-scale online experiment with Ukrainian 
refugees in Poland to measure the link between national identity, pride, 
and the willingness to return to Ukraine. We document a significant 
positive association of national identity and national pride on the 
immediate return intention (‘‘to return as soon as possible’’). Exogenous 
manipulation of identity- and pride-salience produced interesting find-
ings: for people with high levels of dispositional national identity the 
salience increased the return intent, for people with low pride scores 
the pride-salience manipulation backfired. We suggest several explanations for this finding. First, pride-salience 
manipulations might have reminded people…",
