tions of the message employed in our study. It is possible that the 
message failed to generate sufficient salience or motivation, either 
because of an inherently weak first-mover appeal or because recipients 
made a rational assessment that the marginal benefits of participating in 
the seminar were too low. These possibilities suggest that our null 
finding may be context-specific and indicate the need for future research 
