model a worker ’ s utility function U that depends on three arguments: 
utility from income Y , utility from meaning M , and the disutility of effort 
e , which negatively enters the model as the cost of exerting effort C ( e ) . Income Y is a function of wages w and effort e with decreasing marginal 
returns to effort. In both models, workers choose an effort level that 
equalizes the marginal benefits from income and meaning with the 
marginal costs of exerting effort. Unlike Cassar and Meier, who assume 
fixed effort, and later extensions ( Kesternich et al., 2021 ; De Schouwer 
et al., 2023 ) that allow endogenous effort, our model assumes the 
disutility of effort decreases with rising motivation. It also introduces a 
minimum motivation threshold required to exert effort and to derive 
utility from meaningful work — a feature absent in preference-based 
models. We conjecture that work meaningfulness arises from the interplay 
between the work environment and the individual ’ s psychological needs 
for autonomy, competence, and relatedness, which shape motivation a . As a result, meaningfulness enters the utility function as M ( a ) . For 
instance, an employer may grant the same level of autonomy to all 
employees, yet individuals can perceive it differently depending on their 
preference for and understanding of independent work. 3
