Second, correlational analysis can serve as a proxy although it does not 
allow for causal insights. Together with theoretical considerations on 
the direction of causality it is another pragmatic alternative. 7. Contributions
The main contribution is the empirical examination of the relation -
ship between happiness and WTC. This relationship had not been 
examined methodically before to my best knowledge, despite already 
being raised as an open question in the literature ( Buser et al., 2024 ). Notwithstanding expectations to the contrary, happiness did not change 
willingness to compete. Importantly, I explain these differences by 
showing that subjective preferences (competitiveness and task confi -
dence) are mediators of these effects. These subjective variables measure 
how competitive subjects think they are and how many tasks they will 
be able to complete. I find a high correlation between the real-effort and 
incentive-compatible experimental measure of WTC and the simple 
questionnaire measure. Moreover, the findings show some overlap with 
a null result in the literature examining choices ( Hanley et al., 2016 ). Together with research that successfully identifies effects, I therefore 
contribute to establishing patterns of happiness-related and 
non-happiness related constructs. Lastly, I contribute by extending the 
types of samples used from what are often student or sometimes field 
experiments to online experiments ( Kessel et al., 2021 ; Lane, 2017 ; 
Niederle & Vesterlund, 2007 ). 8. Conclusion
I test the effect of happiness on WTC using two incentive-compatible 
experiments. I find no link between happiness and WTC. Exploratory 
analyses reveal that a potential reason for the lack of an effect of 
happiness is that positive affect does not change subjective competi -
tiveness and task confidence, which are relevant to behaviour in this 
context. This contrasts with other variables such as gender that correl…",
